Scientists have found a way to discover the relative stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California at Santa Cruz have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical uniformity in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow to search among stars related, that is, arisen from one cluster.
The authors published their findings in the journal Nature, and a brief summary of the findings is available on the university's website.
The reason for the similar chemical composition of the nearest stars is the turbulent mixing of gas clouds prior to the formation of stars.
Even if a newborn star leaves the cluster, its chemical composition can be used to determine its birthplace and the region of formation of its parent stars.
Scientists had previously doubted that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could produce a chemical difference between it and its relatives in the cluster.
The results of modeling conducted by astrophysicists show that such differences should not occur.
In their study, the researchers used a supercomputer to model two streams of interstellar gas that together formed the cloud.
Over the course of several million years, this object is being transformed by its own gravity into a cluster in which protostars are beginning to form.
The scientists added paint-marks to the original gas streams and found that rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud achieved a high degree of chemical uniformity.
Astrophysicists say their research proves that it is possible to search for chemical relatives to stars, and to identify possible regions of formation of such objects.
