Recalling the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights.
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed legislation that protects union organization as a civil right.
"Where there are unions, there are middle-class jobs", says Allison, a Minnesota Democrat who is co-chair of the Progressive Caucus.
That's why I'm proud to present the Workers' Empowerment Act along with the symbol of the civil rights movement, John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill will give workers the same legal standing against discrimination against union organizing as against other forms of discrimination, by stopping the forces of anti-union activists
Amending the Labor Relations Act to allow workers who face discrimination for union membership to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive damages and fines - is a sensible and necessary initiative.
But it's certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Allison, Lewis and the co-authors of the bill are proposing is to remember a very American idea.
Despite the attacks that unions have faced in recent years -- in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country -- Americans once supported countries around the world to embrace, expand and respect labor rights.
There was a time, as millions of Americans remember, when this country stood up for democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the militarised autocracy of Hideki Tojo was replaced by a democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions play a role in shaping the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that "the workers' right to organize, to negotiate and to collectively act is guaranteed".
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that ensured that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: "The right to form associations for the purpose of protecting and improving working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or field of activity.
Agreements which restrict or seek to restrict this right shall have no legal force; measures designed to that end shall be declared unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which would be adopted by the United Nations as a worldwide agreement in 1948, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and to join trade unions for the protection of his interests".
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic position that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to build civil and democratic societies, the Americans explained that the right to organize unions -- and for that union to participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies -- must be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As the Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now, everyone knows that the labor movement didn't undermine the nation's strength, but it did increase it.
By raising the living standards of millions, the trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers, and so should we.
The formal recognition of labor rights as human rights - and the expansion of civil rights protections to prevent discrimination against labor organizations - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are reviving the ideals that historically enlarged America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
A judge temporarily blocks a bill that could shut down all abortion clinics in Louisiana.
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the passage of a Louisiana law that supporters say will likely shut down all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under the measure, which was signed into law by Louisiana Governor Bobby Djinald in June and was set to take effect on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have hospital admissions within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge's ruling means that for now, doctors can continue to perform legal abortions while continuing to seek such authority.
"The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while continuing to pursue their power of attorney", wrote Judge John deGravells in his decision.
The hearing will be held within a month of the judge making a more permanent ruling under this law.
Abortion rights advocates welcomed the ruling, the latest in a series of rulings against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital privileges.
"Today's ruling ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from a malicious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights", said Nancy Northup, president and CEO of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which has filed a lawsuit to block the law on behalf of three of the state's five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the ruling applied to the doctors from the two clinics, which were not plaintiffs in the case and also applied for admissions.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed similar laws, and courts recently ruled such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of a Texas law that would have shut down most of the remaining clinics in the state were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion rights advocates, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say that access laws place restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion object that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has hospital admissions authority, according to the Center for Reproductive Rights.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing the procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing the procedure, the group said.
Criticising the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while their applications for admission powers are pending.
What will the introduction of quotas for domestic products lead to
At least half of the products in each type of goods in the assortment of trading networks should be of Russian production, according to the State Duma deputy from the "Fair Russia" faction Oleg Nilov.
The parliamentarian has drafted a bill to introduce protective measures against domestic producers, the newspaper "Izvestia" writes.
The document will be further detailed to avoid possible inconvenience to buyers.
For the rest of the products that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic producers", - said Nilov.
Along with amendments to the article "On the Basics of State Regulation of Trade Activities in the Russian Federation", the bill provides for the introduction of changes to the Tax Code, which establishes a reduced rate of VAT of 10% when selling products produced in Russia.
The idea of introducing a 50% interest rate quota in retail chains is part of a package of incentive measures for Russian manufacturers.
The stalls will be several times the size of the domestic ones.
But the initiative can have both positive and negative effects, experts say.
According to Sergey Litvinenko, a lawyer for the company "Nalogovik" and a member of the independent expert center "Public Duma", for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive, and will lead to growth.
The big winners are the farmers, the small shops.
They'll be able to sell more, which means more profits.
They will also have the power to dictate their terms and prices to retailers, who will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian manufacturers will be able to increase their activity and sales, which will lead to higher taxes than before.
It will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will start to expand, some will be mastered faster, and it will contribute to GDP growth.
Russia's dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, but not immediately", the expert notes.
Previously, Russian businesses often could not get into local stores because of the high competition from foreign counterparts.
Now that the embargo has been lifted, that niche is open to a sigh of relief.
But we should not forget that after all the necessary approvals and sanitary inspections, food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia will enter the Russian market.
In other words, it's a "quiet moment" when the old players have left and the new ones have not yet arrived.
After almost a month, we can speak of increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as the price increase for finished products", - told AIF.ru the first Vice-President of the Russian public organization "Russian Club of Financial Directors", k.e.n. Tamara Kasyanova.
The idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will definitely allow the sector to be anchored to local producers.
In that case, they would be competing with each other, not with goods that are cheaper because of the subsidies of another country.
In other words, the competition for the buyer will be between companies operating under the same industry laws.
On the other hand, Kasyanova notes, Russian producers are not able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of compatriots in all items.
And in this situation, the trade networks will have to "pull" the share of Russian goods to half of the range.
This has led to fears that the stores will be sold with substandard products.
Foreign products with broken labels may be sold as Russian products", the expert adds.
The negative effect of the quotas will be felt by the large retail chains, especially those that benefit from the cooperation with importers.
Logically, this would also hurt foreign suppliers themselves, as demand for their products would decline.
Litvinenko does not rule out that the law on quotas for domestic goods may affect consumers.
The fact is that some Russian-made products may be inferior in quality to imported counterparts, while stores may raise prices to second-rate, as for scarce goods.
The idea of import substitution, which was forgotten in the early 2000s, was revived by economists in February this year due to the ongoing devaluation of the ruble.
Now, with the difficult relationship with the West, the issue of refusing imported products becomes even more urgent.
The law is designed to oblige retailers to consider domestic manufacturers when forming orders to suppliers.
Then we will be able to move forward much faster and more confidently on the path of import substitution, and the system of planning production for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time", says Deputy Oleg Nilov.
The quota mechanism will be particularly effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential is particularly high, for example in the dairy sector, where imports accounted for 25%.
Our farmers are really capable of completely covering the shelves of Russian stores.
Meat production could also be given a powerful boost.
As you know, the largest share of imports is kept on beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% of the production is still Russian", Kasyanova said.
Experts believe that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will help to replace imports and may accelerate this process.
However, this initiative will not lead to import substitution by itself, as this requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is convinced.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be imported from abroad, which means that full import substitution will not happen, but significant steps will be taken in this direction.
It's not enough to set quotas, we have to establish domestic production in the country to meet these quotas.
These quotas are just such guarantees that will provide", the expert states.
Poor diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer kills more women in rural areas than in urban areas.
Angelina Jolie and her brother James released a video in memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who are incubating in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those living in urban areas.
Researchers analyzed the medical records of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, and found that only 35 percent survived five years after the diagnosis.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute for Medical Research reported that the likelihood of dying during the study was 20 percent higher for those living in the state's rural and remote areas than for those living in urban areas.
RESEARCH: New drugs may slow the growth of lung and ovarian cancers
Researchers tracked the women's medical care over seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that a woman's age at diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, current medical history, and socioeconomic status also affected her survival.
Older women and those who had cancer in the later stages at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in regional or remote areas of the state, the likelihood of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
While the study was not designed to determine why women living outside of cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that a late diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
"This disease is best treated by gynecological surgeons, and they are mostly in big cities", she said.
While improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of out-of-home services, which would allow specialists to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people receiving treatment away from home, could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographical location, the study found that longevity among women with ovarian cancer was rare, highlighting the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by the Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elishe Niv, was told she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
