Inflation is off the holidays.
Will Russians feel the sharp rise in prices
As a result of the cross-sanctions of the Russian Federation and the West, inflation in Russia will accelerate and not conform to the forecasts of the authorities, VTB Capital analysts are convinced.
Experts believe that the delayed effects of anti-sanctions will lead to an inflation shock in the first quarter of 2015, writes RBC Daily.
According to the latest forecast of the Ministry of Economic Development, in 2014 the inflation will be 6.5-7.5%, and next year even less - 6.5%.
However, according to Kommersant, this week the Ministry of Economic Development is due to make "small but fundamental" adjustments to the macroeconomic forecast for 2017.
According to the publication, the department may lower the inflation estimate for 2015, which will eliminate the expected zero growth in the income of the population.
The forecast assumed that the food sanctions of the Russian Federation will be in force for one year - until August 2015.
How could such a high inflation be predicted in such a situation?
The current situation implies a one-time shock, but the downward trend of inflation will not change", - said the source of the newspaper in the Ministry of Finance.
Economists at VTB Capital do not share the government's financial-economic bloc's expectations regarding inflation and forecast price growth at 8% in 2014.
The main effect of the food bans will come with the possible introduction of sales tax (SST) in Russian regions in 2015, experts believe.
Inflation will peak at 9% in February, after which the annual rate of price growth will decline, experts believe.
By the way, last week Rosstat released the first inflation results after Russia introduced "careful sanctions".
AIF.ru polled experts and found out their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, head of the analytical department of AForex FC:
Prices are already rising in the main product segments.
Moreover, as the prices of socially important products increased, the government was forced to introduce measures for systematic monitoring of price stability in order to prevent risks of unjustified price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers already report on a daily basis to regulators so that the authorities know exactly who, when and for what reason is initiating price increases.
The key factors driving the consumer price index continue to be the huge capital outflows, the excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian mega-regulator, the internal conversion due to the flight of the population into foreign currency, and the embargo on the import of food products from countries that have joined the sanctions against Russia.
If inflationary pressures had been kept under control, the cost of a minimum-priced grocery basket would not have jumped 12% in a single quarter.
The ban on the import of foodstuffs caused a supply shock in the domestic market and led to a perfectly logical increase in the final cost.
Since at the current stage we are not able to fully launch the mechanism of import substitution, as well as increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market through domestic production, the retaliatory sanctions will continue to carry the risks of growth of the inflationary component.
Add to this the fiscal reasons related to the lack of confidence in the national currency, as well as the deteriorated economic growth prospects, and inflation could well exceed 8% by the end of this year.
Alexander Razuvaev, director of the analytical department of Alpari
In the 1990s, inflation was sometimes 20-30% per month, and in the zero years it was also above the current level, but that was offset by the rapid economic growth.
I think the inflation rate will be between 8 and 8.5 percent by the end of the year.
Platon Maguta, managing director of the Maguta Foundation
The external factor of the sanctions against Russia is being successfully contained, but if there is further pressure, especially on the financial sector, it could lead to certain difficulties and increase inflation expectations of the population, which usually traditionally manifests itself in the purchase of cash currency in order to protect their savings.
It is possible to assume that the government, the Russian Central Bank and the Ministry of Finance will try to mitigate the gradual weakening of the ruble, both by market methods and by state regulation.
But price increases have traditionally started after the summer's lull and may be more pronounced this fall.
The target consumer inflation rate of 7.5% in Russia is likely to stand, as the Russian Federation still has financial reserves.
Gardening centers are saddened by the decline in homeownership
Such a drop, driven by a dramatic decline in homeownership among those under 35, could see garden centres losing tens of millions of pounds a year as today's young consumers reach the "basic age of gardening", according to a study by the HTA reported by the Financial Times.
According to this report, renters spend on average 55 percent of the amount that homeowners spend on gardening.
It mentions the increase in the number of people living in highly urbanised areas without gardens, the popularity of asphalting yards in front of the house for parking and the reduction in the size of gardens as other factors threatening an industry estimated to have annual sales of £5 billion.
Greater London, where home ownership has fallen from 61 per cent to 43 per cent in six years, has the lowest rate of household gardeners spending in the UK.
The HTA and the Royal Horticultural Society have said that renting out housing and not having space for a garden doesn't mean people can't grow plants.
Geithner Barter, chief gardening adviser at RHS, said: "Cannons, for example, are especially popular with tenants who can take their plants with them when they move".
The HTA report defined the period between 1997 and 2005 as a "golden age" of retail gardening goods as a result of the increase in homeowners and economic prosperity from the late 1980s to the mid-1990s.
It also predicts that the market will improve this year due to better weather after unfavorable conditions in March and April last year.
