China's biggest companies have united against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China's largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and internet giants Tencent Holdings (social network, messenger, etc.) and Baidu (the largest Chinese search engine), are creating a company that will compete with Alibaba in the online trading market.
But catching up with the Chinese Internet miracle, which has even outstripped its American rivals, eBay and Amazon.com, will be a challenge.
The Union of the Largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in the joint venture, with 70 percent of the money to be owned by Wanda and 15 percent each by the internet companies, according to a Wanda Group statement.
The company is planning to register in Hong Kong.
The joint venture will combine Baidu search with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China, with about 438 million users), Tencent and Wanda infrastructure.
In addition to its network of 40 luxury hotels, the Wanda Group operates at least 49 commercial properties throughout China and 40 shopping malls.
Last year , the company invested 50 billion yuan (over $ 8 billion) in the construction of a film studio and theme park in Qingdao (a city in the east of China on the shores of the Yellow Sea).
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors annually and generate revenues of $960 million.
Wanda is also owned by American movie theater chain AMC Entertainment Holdings, making it the largest movie theater operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all its shopping malls, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, which will be developed by its upcoming rival Alibaba.
According to Dong Tse, who will head the new company, the merger will enable Wanda to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million to 100 million by next year.
The new platform is set to become the world's largest online-to-offline platform, says Dong Ze.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract buyers on the Internet so that they come to traditional offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O is coupon-selling services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
"O2O is the biggest pie in online commerce", said Wanda's chief executive Wang Jianlin, quoted by Bloomberg.
"There is no real O2O platform in China now, and in this situation, everyone has roughly equal chances", he said.
China's e-commerce market is the largest in the world, and McKinsey & Co. estimates that it will more than triple to $395 billion by 2015 from 2011.
China's Internet users have grown to 632 million, according to Bloomberg's official statistics, more than the population of any country in the world except India.
And by 2015, that number is projected to grow to 850 million.
The League of the Richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huaten was China's richest man until recently, but according to Bloomberg's billionaire index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already overtaken him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma's net worth is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion is due to his stake in Alibaba.
Baidu CEO Robin Lee is now the third richest man in China, while Wanda's Wang Jianlin is fourth.
"It's very interesting to watch this battle: the three richest people are joining forces to challenge the even richer", said Cao Lei, director of the China E-Commerce Research Center in Hangzhou, to Bloomberg.
But he thinks the new company is unlikely to be able to seriously compete with Alibaba right after it was founded: "Rome wasn't built in a day".
It is not easy to compete with Alibaba, not only new companies, but also the well-deserved leaders of global online commerce, as evidenced by the financial report published on the eve of Alibaba's last quarter.
Alibaba is often described as something between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June, the Chinese company made more money than both of its American rivals combined.
Alibaba's net profit for the period was almost double the similar aggregate of its competitors, almost tripling to $1.99 billion year-on-year.
"Alibaba still has huge money-generating potential, thanks in large part to its mobile apps", commented an analyst at Hong Kong-based Arete Research Service on the Bloomberg report.
According to an updated prospectus on Alibaba's website, the US Securities and Exchange Commission, the number of active mobile users of the company's services in July was 188 million, significantly higher than the March figure (163 million).
And 32.8 percent of all Alibaba transactions in the last quarter were on mobile devices.
Alibaba is going to announce the value of its stock before the IPO.
According to the average valuation of 11 analysts polled by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after the stock sale.
According to Bloomberg sources, Alibaba's debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) could be as early as September 16.
The company's road show, which precedes the event, will kick off on September 3.
Alibaba's IPO is expected to be the largest in NYSE history and bring in about $20 billion.
The previous record holder was Visa, which in 2008 made an initial public offering of $17.9 billion.
At least half of the food in the retail chains should be Russian-made, state Duma deputies say.
They've drafted a bill to do that.
It is about making changes to the article 8 of the Federal Law "On the Basics of the State Regulation of Trade Activities in the Russian Federation" and to the Tax Code.
The purpose of the document is to introduce protective measures against Russian food producers.
An important clarification, according to the bill, at least 50 percent of domestic products in stores must be for each type of goods.
However, the document will take into account that there are goods that are not produced in Russia, for example, vegetables and fruits in winter, so they will be made "discounted" to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
The bill also amends the Russian Tax Code to lower the VAT rate by 10 percent for all food products from Russia, the newspaper Izvestiya reported.
On August 27, a bill was introduced in the lower house of parliament to amend the Federal Law "On Retail Markets", which proposes to revive farmers' markets in Russia, where small producers can sell their products.
Police Chief Magaluf is charged with corruption
The plaintiffs presented evidence of extortion by police and Calvià municipal officials to the Mallorca state prosecutor's office on Friday.
The police chief of Calvia on the resort island of Mallorca has been arrested following allegations of corruption by businessmen and bar owners in the notorious centre of drunken revelry, Magaluf.
Chief Inspector José Antonio Navarro has been placed under guard as a result of corruption charges brought against him by several businessmen from Punta Ballena, the street where most of Magaluf's bars and nightclubs are located.
According to the daily online publication Mallorca Diario, the plaintiffs presented evidence of extortion by police and Calvia municipality officials to the Mallorca anti-corruption prosecutor's office on Friday.
Two other local police officers were arrested by the Spanish National Guard on corruption charges and will be questioned by the judge along with Navarro.
Spanish daily ABC reported that disgruntled nightclub owners say protectionism by the authorities is seriously affecting their businesses.
"It's not about making money anymore, it's about survival", one businessman told the court.
We cannot put our livelihoods at risk.
We have nothing to lose.
