The first day of spring marked wet and windy conditions affecting flights at Adelaide Airport
A COLD spring surprise in the south of South Australia brought torrential rains and strong winds that affected flights at Adelaide Airport.
Another 5mm of rain fell on the city by 9pm, following 6.6mm that fell on Sunday night.
The latest rain was preceded by a pair of short showers with gusty winds, including a thunderstorm that began shortly before 8 p.m. and dumped nearly 4 mm in about 10 minutes.
After winter released an early spring last week, temperatures fell again on Monday to a city-wide high of 15.8C.
The poor weather conditions are believed to have been one of the reasons for the delay in boarding a Virgin Airlines flight from Melbourne to Adelaide.
The plane was scheduled to land just after 7:30 p.m., but it was caught in a wind shift - a sudden change in wind speed or direction over a short distance - and was forced to gain altitude.
Wind gusts reached 50 km/h over land at Adelaide Airport at this time.
Flight data showed that the plane had to gain altitude during the second landing, and the plane finally landed at about 8:40 p.m.
The delay of this flight caused the subsequent delay of several other flights, including Emirates from Dubai and Qantas from Sydney.
A high of 16C is forecast for Adelaide on Tuesday with a chance of one or two downpours.
The estimate of construction objects in the Russian Federation will be calculated in a new way
The Federal Antimonopoly Service is taking special control of pricing, regulation of the construction industry, as well as problems of connection to networks.
The FAS has created an expert council for the development of competition in the construction sector.
At the meeting, the head of the FAS Housing, Construction and Natural Resources Control Vadim Solovyov said that "today's estimate of construction facilities is absolutely incomprehensible".
The regulatory framework makes pricing opaque and can lead to unreasonable construction costs, according to the FAS.
And they propose to determine the cost of construction of state-owned objects at the design stage on the basis of market prices of design solutions instead of the currently applied estimated norms and unit prices for technological operations.
These proposals have been put on the road map and are now being considered by the Ministry of Construction.
"The replacement of traditional construction estimates with calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry", explained Vadim Solovyev to RGB.
Because every bolt and nut is counted in the estimate, it is not always possible to check everything, so sometimes unscrupulous construction companies can bury "whole tractors" in the documentation.
The Ministry agrees with the FAS.
"The first work on the transition to calculating the cost of the construction elements is already there: developed methods for calculating prices for the construction solutions, the compilation of estimates on these indicators, - told "RGB" the head of the Department of urban planning and architecture of the Ministry of construction, Yelena Zhukova.
The road construction sector was chosen as a pilot.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
As told "RGB" the head of the construction company "Profi-invest" Anatoly Demyanko, the estimated standards are long outdated, but another mechanism is not yet proposed to the business.
"As for the proposed calculations for structural elements, it is difficult to implement in practice, as the construction of buildings often uses completely different technologies", he says.
It's no secret that the construction industry is developing largely because of government orders.
According to the chairman of the board of the National Company "Expert Community of Professionals of the State Order" Ekaterina Lezina, today the state is the most capable customer.
Vladimir Malakhov, deputy director of engineering at Rosatom's capital construction branch center, drew attention to the fact that today the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to the portfolio of contracts and companies that have monopoly competences and do not allow competitors to enter the field.
He believes that a transparent market can only be created when access to contracts is as free as possible from the influence of a controlling party.
At the expert council it was proposed to form the system of state orders in such a way that the same executor does not have the right to receive more than one contract for the amount of more than 1 billion rubles or several contracts for the amount of more than 1 billion rubles.
The Ministry believes that this approach should be evaluated in terms of the impact on business, as well as the efficiency of construction management.
As Elena Zhukova explained, in this case it will be necessary to endow the customer with the functions of the general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the number of staff of the customer and budgetary expenditures for its maintenance.
In this case, the customer's specialists will have to have knowledge to evaluate the quality of the work performed by the contractor organizations, as well as their safety.
Often, this breakdown will require determining who will be responsible for the security of the facility as a whole.
In addition, this approach may lead to an outflow of highly qualified participants in public procurement due to lack of interest in obtaining a state order for an incomplete volume of work and a small amount of contract.
The deputy head of the expert-consulting center of the Institute of Purchases, Alexander Yevstachenkov, believes that now the procedure of state procurement has turned into a business game for the attention of the contractor.
And he gave this example: "the participant when filling out the application should indicate "specific indicators" without specifying the words: "or equivalent", "must be", "from", "more", "less", "analogue", "or", "type", "of the same type", "not lower", "lower", "higher", "may", "may have", "may be", "earlier", "not earlier", "not higher", "not allowed" etc.
Thus, the contracting authorities often abuse their right to impose requirements on the content of the tender submitted by the contracting entities.
Another problem with the 44-FZ, according to Yevstachenkov, was the need to assess the quality of work through the "paper" proposal of the participant at the stage of application.
Considering the participant's application, it is only possible to evaluate the contractor's qualification, but not the quality of the work, which has not even been started, - the expert believes.
The quality of the work can only be judged when it is accepted.
The expert council also proposed to shift the marginal revenue from the top to the bottom echelon, to make the middleman contractors disappear.
Chairman of the expert council, state secretary, deputy head of the FAS Andrei Tsarikovsky believes that this is not worth doing, since the general contractor should be responsible for the order.
Otherwise, it's like the famous Arkadyr Raikin's "Ateliers" refrain: "Are there any complaints about the buttons?"
Israeli children return to school after Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in the Gaza Strip returned to school on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters as rockets and mortars rained down on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in Gaza remained closed as the territory recovered from the fighting.
The start of school brought a sense of joy and excitement to the missile-stricken communities of southern Israel, but the traces of the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, the staff of the Pasosh kindergarten, which was hit by a missile, removed the traces of shrapnel from the walls and the children's playground before the arrival of the students.
"We are a little afraid, but we are looking forward to the future", said Ronit Barth, a resident of Kibbutz Saad and an English teacher at his school.
A lot of kids in our neighborhood really need to get back to a life of measurement.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said that going back to school was "a little strange".
"It was a difficult time, and we did not go out of our homes at all", she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited a kibbutz near the Gaza border to express his support.
Until a ceasefire agreement ended the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad stayed indoors or left their homes, moving to safer areas farther from the Gaza Strip to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a Palestinian landmine shrapnel, are questioning whether they should go back.
The Ministry of Education reports that about a dozen families are still missing.
Their children were sent to other schools for the time being.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a town on the border with Gaza that has aged badly from the Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study hard and said, "We will do everything we can to give you knowledge and to ensure your safety".
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite ceasefire last Tuesday.
The ceasefire agreement ended the fighting immediately, but left key issues unresolved, such as Hamas' demands for the lifting of the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new round of indirect talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
The war killed over 2,100 Palestinians, three-quarters of them civilians, and at least 494 children, according to Palestinian and UN estimates.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; however, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this claim.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians were killed, including one Thai worker.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza militants fired 4,591 rockets and mines at Israeli cities, mostly in the south.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, has conducted more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
Thousands of homes in Gaza have been damaged or destroyed by Israeli attacks, and an estimated 250,000 people have taken refuge in more than 100 schools that have been converted into shelters.
With tens of thousands of people still in shelters and the fighting continuing, officials in charge of education last week postponed the start of the school year.
"I hope that the school will open soon so that we can complete our education like children around the world and Jewish children", said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in a school in Gaza.
According to a popular measure, property prices have shown the biggest winter increase in seven years.
The RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic home price index for the Australian capital increased by 1.1 percent in August, RP data reported on Monday.
This led to a combined increase of June, July and August of 4.2 percent, the largest increase in a winter month since 2007.
The annual price increase was 10.9 percent, more than double the 12-month increase to August 2013, but the increase was not evenly distributed across the country.
RP Data research director Tim Lawless reported that Sydney and Melbourne are leading a two-tier market.
RP Data figures show that Sydney's house prices have risen by 16.1 percent over the past year, while Melbourne's prices have risen by 11.7 percent.
The next markets to gain were Adelaide, Brisbane and Darwin, where prices rose by an average of five to six per cent.
At the other end of the scale was Canberra, which had gone through government spending cuts, where prices rose by only 1.4 percent a year.
Mr. Lawless said that now that spring has begun, there will be an increase in the number of properties listed for sale over the next few months, which will be a "real test" for the market.
"Given the current high level of auction speed, the overall high sales speed and the current low interest rate conditions, it is likely that the value of housing will still rise over the next three months", he said.
How people live in the oldest house in Ufa
In the former house of goldsmiths and mining engineers Evdokim and his son Ivan Demidov on October Revolution Street 57/1 (formerly the Great Kazan) 18 apartments.
The house from the XVIII century has not changed since the construction, except for the deterioration.
Outsiders come here as an excursion, and the residents suffer more than they rejoice, from their privilege - the right to live in the oldest house of Ufa, whose walls are remembered by the commander Alexander Suvorov.
The date of the house's construction is not accurate, historians point to two dates - 1730 and 1737.
But anyway, it turns out the building is almost 300 years old.
The old courtyard, the door always open, the creaky staircase.
The doors to the apartments are close together, the walls are cracked, and in the openings from the shredded plaster, the street is visible in places.
It seems to be based on an honest word.
And the locals say, "You don't think so, but that's the way it is".
Living in a wooden house from the 18th century is very difficult, says Tatyana Lukyanova, a resident of apartment No. 3.
The property is on the National Register, but the money for its upkeep hasn't been paid for decades, and we feel like museum pieces that the authorities have simply forgotten about.
It's been 40 years since the last renovation.
The walls are still pretty much intact, but the foundation is all rotted.
Many residents still use the outdoor toilet and bathe once a week in the public bath.
How can you be satisfied under these conditions?!
The road goes right under the windows, there's no pedestrian zone.
Tatiana is pulling back the curtain.
Now you see what you've only heard before: a stream of cars coming through the windows.
You see, the glass is shattered all the time, the windows are closed, and we're used to the noise.
But you get used to it, good and bad.
Our apartment is still exemplary, thanks to my husband, his hands are golden.
We have two rooms, we live together with our son.
Other families have much worse conditions, with ceilings on the second floor that are just over five feet high.
To contrast, Tatyana suggests to go to visit the neighbor from apartment No. 6 Ludmila Starostyna.
A friendly, hospitable woman on the doorstep offers a cup of coffee and with a sad smile says:
We have a one-room apartment, 14 square meters for four people, and this is how we live: my husband and I and our daughter and granddaughter.
I've been here since I was born, there's never been another living space. Ludmila looks around the room: the sofas, two sofas with the letter "g"; on one of them is her granddaughter with a laptop.
Very close and little differs from the usual domestic interior: only the ceilings are beautiful, "historical".
But the ceiling is leaking regularly, the plumbing is no good.
Lyudmila speaks of her apartment in a casual and surprising way, as an Italian woman whose house stands on Roman ruins.
So it boils down to one very old and recent, everyday and legendary:
The water pipe was last repaired about 40 years ago.
Then they made us a little kitchen in the corner and a toilet out of the old closet.
We live in the same apartment where Demidov and his family lived, with servants on the second floor.
Our apartment is not privatized, and why?
The real estate agency says privatization is irrelevant.
We'll only get the one-bedroom apartment anyway, we can't claim more.
Four months ago, they promised to move us, but nothing happened.
I'm not used to complaining, and I won't.
A whole dynasty lived in this apartment (room)! My grandparents, my mother and father, my husband and I, my daughter and granddaughter.
Things have happened in that time.
Like, there were these big rats running around the kitchen.
Look at the walls of the wing, they're three feet thick!
They say the solution was mixed with eggs, which is why it lasts so long.
The house is well built, thanks to Demidov!
I guess that's why no one's been killed by a collapsed ceiling or a pile of wood.
But the building is slowly dying before our eyes: the boards and logs of the house are rotting, the floors have repeatedly failed, we have poured cement, but all to no avail - the solution goes into the ground like a well.
They say it is, that there is a secret passageway under our room and a passage to the White River, which was specially made by the Old Believers who once lived here, so that they could hide from danger, in case.
They were being pursued.
Lyudmila Starostina tells how some historian came to them, begged to let him start excavating in the apartment.
And then convinced them to give them a living space in exchange for his one on October Avenue.
Ludmila refused the historian:
Where are we going, the four of us?
And there's a small hope that they'll make the house more spacious.
If we agreed to trade, we wouldn't have won anything.
The Old Ones didn't win anything, though.
Ludmila's biggest dream is to have them moved in, and her daughter and 16-year-old granddaughter given a separate room.
So two families have been allocated a two-bedroom apartment instead of the not-so-magnificent ruins that two generations now live in.
A cute, miniature girl Olesya Karsakova from apartments 11 and 12 shows the second floor of the house.
There, in two narrow rooms of 75 square feet [23 sq m], called apartments, lives her large family.
There are seven of us, two children.
You see the conditions.
The stucco falls off in pieces, like the window frames, and the walls in the kitchen and the rooms have gaping holes.
The water in the tap is cold all year round.
If you walk through the apartments of the oldest house in Ufa, you can see that the Lavrentyev couple from apartment No. 4 were the luckiest of all.
They occupy the largest rooms on the first floor.
You're right, there's plenty of room!
75 square feet, three people registered.
We live in the same rooms where legend has it that Suvorov stayed during his stay in Ufa, - says the head of the family Alexander Dmitrievich Lavrentyev.
The ceilings are high, the space is great.
The only thing that's bad is that everything is falling apart, falling apart, falling apart.
The neighbours must have told you!
The worst part was the floors, the wooden planks rotting, the ground literally falling from under us.
I've got the supports, the clamp, the hall is empty, and in the other room we're walking, swinging on the swings, so shaky.
Alexander Dmitrievich can tell you more about the house of the merchant Yevdokim Demidov than any guide.
He treats the goldsmith like his own son, speaks of him with admiration.
Indeed, the personality was extraordinary: the owner of the Kagina and Uzyan factories built houses, cast cannons and bells, kept the Ural mines.
The heirs of the commercial real estate are proud of their ancestors, but they don't want to live under the same roof with history anymore.
I settled here as a child, in the 1940s, - says Alexander Dmitrievich.
At that time, wooden carriage rooms, stables and guard booths were built around the building, which were later demolished.
In 1968, they wanted to clear our house, but something prevented...
In 2014, the same thing happened: they were given new housing.
We were collecting all the paperwork, and we were running around, and we found out that the move was postponed to 2015 or 2016.
We don't believe in any of this anymore.
Two years ago, Lavrentyev went to the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Bashkortostan to find out about the fate of the house.
The tenant's been denied.
They were sent from one table to another, and then, as a joke, they were given a piece of paper without a signature and a stamp: "The Ministry of Culture does not object to the resettlement of the tenants".
I have a feeling that our house is no longer in the city plan, because it was first at number 57, then 57A, and now 57/1.
It's like it was torn down in the '70s.
"Russian Planet" has appealed to the head of the sector of information and analytical work of the land resources management of Ufa Vladimir Barabash.
The house at 57/1 October Revolution Street is included in the program of resettlement of dilapidated housing.
I can't be responsible for the actions of the officials in the 70s, but I know that at that time there was a plan to demolish all the old houses, despite their historical importance.
Fortunately, this did not happen, and the decision of the modern authorities - to restore all the old houses on the street of the October Revolution, representing architectural value, - is successfully implemented.
The residents will be moved to new apartments soon.
According to Barabash, the restoration of the House of Demidov will be done by Italian specialists who participated in the restoration of buildings in Venice.
There's an architecture biennale in Italy right now, and the Old Ufa project is one of the other ones.
I hope that by 2016 the entire former Stara Kazanska street will be restored, - says the official.
The house will have a proper look, like it was before, three centuries ago.
Demidov's house will most likely become a museum open to all.
In addition, the government has decided to make the street pedestrian on weekends.
Unfortunately, we can't do it in the morning, because the traffic is too heavy in the city.
Vladimir Barabash promises to resettle people from the future museum in 2015.
However, they are not likely to be satisfied: Their new apartments will have the same floor area as their current ones.
Just from another era.
In Primorye , a forest fire started because of a thunderstorm .
A dry thunderstorm caused a forest fire in the territory of the Ochtnichsky forestry in the Pojarsky district of the Primorsky region.
We're building up the force and resources at the scene.
According to the leadership of the KGSBU "Primorskaya avibaba", the conditions created at the site of the fire require the involvement of aviation forces.
Vasily Medvedev, deputy head of the air base:
The fire, which occurred in a difficult-to-reach area, was detected by an observer pilot from the side of the patrol airship An-2 on an area of 3 hectares.
The wood is burning on the old fireplace.
The heavy swamped terrain and steep slopes of more than 45 degrees, the lack of suitable landing sites for fire-landing creates considerable difficulties in extinguishing.
We need an Mi-8.
The delivery of forces at the disposal of the airbase by the Mi-2 helicopter and the An-2 aircraft is very difficult.
After the fire was discovered, 4 firefighters were dispatched to the fire extinguishing area.
The main task of the specialists is to put out the fire and prepare the site for the delivery of additional forces and fire extinguishing equipment.
