As soon as the landing site for the helicopter in the area of the fire is ready, specialists will be transferred to the fire extinguishing site, according to the website of the administration of the Primorsky Territory.
Lennie Henry: My father never hugged me.
Never said "I love you"
Henry was one of seven children born to a family of Jamaican immigrants in Dudley in the Midlands in 1958.
His father, who died when Henry was 19, worked in a factory, and their relationship was limited.
Henry rehearses a comedy, Rudy's Rare Records, which is partly based on imaginary conversations with his father and grew out of a series of shows on Radio 4.
The soundtrack is a mix of reggae and rap, and the melodies are lively.
But Henry had to work through some difficult childhood memories.
After his mother's death, there was "a lot" of treatment, and Henry often reflects on his relationship with his father.
He was very inaccessible.
You never saw his face, you only heard his voice, "Stop making noise.
Get away from your sister.
Move it out!
I want to watch cricket.
My older brothers Seymour and Hilton, who were grown-ups when I was a child, would go with him to the pub and talk about things like the shape of a beer glass, the beauty of a cricket stroke.
I've never spoken to him like that.
He was the kind of grumpy guy in the corner who read the paper most of my life.
Henry had recently opened a foundry in Dudley, and although conditions were better than they had been in his father's day, he was able to glimpse what his life must have been like.
