Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
The Briton said she had spent many years thinking she would die after being misdiagnosed.
Carin Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking she had only a few years left to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, a group of inherited disorders that cause nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK has reported that misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with TMD because so little is known about the condition.
An estimated 23,000 people in the UK are thought to have TNM, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, unsteady gait and pinched toes.
Patients may experience numbness or pain, and the condition is not cured and progresses, meaning that symptoms get worse over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich's Ataxia (AF), a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she'd be in a wheelchair by the time she was 18, and dead by the time she was 30.
A mother of two who is now 51 years old said: "As a child, I knew I could not do what others did.
I fell every day, and I had more time to do everything.
