The tax burden on Washington area businesses is rising as the economy recovers.
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales and more jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country increased modestly last year as the economic recovery accelerated, according to new research published last week, and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in Maryland, Virginia and the District collectively paid $27.6 billion to state and local treasuries in fiscal 2013, 3.8 percent more than the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The state and local business tax burden last year increased 4.3 percent to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after consecutive years when bills were lower, in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes rose faster, 4.3 percent, than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by the professional services firm Ernst & Young and the State Taxation Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county's tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from taxes on entrepreneurs, while 36 percent of Maryland's tax revenue comes from corporate taxes.
Virginia, at 28 percent, brings the lowest amount of tax revenue, proportionally, from business owners.
The increase in tax revenue is largely due to a return to the value of companies' real estate, say the researchers, which has raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three years in a row when growth was less than 1 percent.
While the largest portion of this revenue is coming from large states like California, New York and Texas, it appears that the same is happening in the Washington, D.C., area.
Companies in the District, Maryland and Virginia combined paid $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 - a 4.2 percent increase over the previous year.
However, the observed return on property value has no similar effect on the growth of state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of corporate tax bills.
Virginia and D.C. companies pay about half of their state and local tax bills in the form of property taxes.
"What's happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, is owned either by the government or by nonprofits that don't pay property taxes", said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the state's Taxation Center.
So Maryland has to rely much more on, say, income taxes to pay for the same services that other states have.
The recent surge in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
Entrepreneurs' incomes also seem to be improving, according to this data.
Companies in the region reported state-level corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion in corporate income tax revenues, the most in the region.
Although trends are in the same direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three localities.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average, 4.3 percent, while the growth rate in Maryland was significantly faster, at 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia saw a below-average tax revenue increase of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of the three jurisdictions (each of which had the same corporate rate), at 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the county it is relatively high at 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower state and local taxes for entrepreneurs and, overall, a more favorable climate for entrepreneurs than Maryland.
The county was not assessed in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its neighbor to the south.
North Carolina recently signed legislation lowering the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, as well as Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, this legislation could raise the corporate income tax rate to as high as 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the D.C. area seem to be doing better and thus paying more in state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
The taxes paid to entrepreneurs as individual income taxes by small business owners -- the transitional structure that most small businesses follow -- in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, a much faster rate of growth than taxes for entrepreneurs as a whole.
Researchers say the trend and the rise in business tax revenues across the country is likely to continue this year, with state and local government sales tax revenues up 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington D.C. area may be lagging behind, as the decline in federal spending is affecting the region's labor market.
