Royal Blood's debut album is on sale, a new hope for British rock that has taken rock duos from clubs straight into stadiums.
Royal Blood have only been on the scene for a year, but they've already been nominated for a BBC Music Award, toured with Arctic Monkeys and even had Jimmy Page in the dressing room at a New York concert.
Their self-titled debut album had received 100,000 pre-orders just months before its release, and the contract for its release is in the portfolio of major label Warner Music.
Given the current lamentable state of the music industry, this is a very unusual situation, because it's not just another Lana Del Rey or another sweet-mouthed representative of the new R'n'B, but it's a pair of bullish-looking Britons playing with a level of volume and intensity that was last in vogue a couple of decades ago.
In general, the stakes on the first album, in connection with all the above circumstances were especially high and have already been fully justified.
The duo has taken a name that could be tampered with, except by some desperate hairy metal-smiths, and the blood of some kings, as they think, runs in their veins, too.
Of course, this is all about the heroes of the past Led Zeppelin: like the great quartet, Royal Blood set out to shake the stagnant blood of British rock, taking it to new heights.
It's probably too early to make any predictions about the success of this venture, but there are some things that can be said.
Ten songs, crammed into thirty minutes or so, is not so much a demonstration of phenomenal compositional talent as a confident and powerful declaration of intent.
Some of the qualities of the individual numbers, of course, cannot be denied: for example, the pilot single "Out Of The Black" is characterized by the fact that it is remembered not by the melodic line but by the drum part.
The musicians joke that it's easier to play the song on the piano than it is to play it on the piano.
Also notable are the powerful "Little Monster" and the closing track "Better Strangers" with a Shakespearean quote in the title.
But the truth is that each of these songs would sound great at a hard rock party, but when played in sequence, they all blend into a more or less homogeneous canvas.
And that's not necessarily a bad thing, in fact, it's the opposite.
The strength of Royal Blood is that they don't claim the laurels of the new Lennon and McCartney (more likely they are aiming at the successors of Motörhead), but have brought out numerous rock duos from the ghetto indie clubs.
Their music, despite some variety, is designed for stadiums, in a space designed for less than a couple of thousand people, it is obviously cramped.
The secret is partly in the clever use of the bass, which replaced the guitar in the usual format, invented in the early zeroes of The White Stripes.
But it's not just the instruments, it's the approach to songwriting.
The heroes of retro-rock zeroes with great difficulty chose outside the postmodern paradigm, with great reluctance went to the point of recognizing themselves not just epigones, but independent creative units.
Royal Blood already sound so powerful and arrogant that this effort successfully drapes some of the secondary and hard-headedness of the musical material.
After all, who says rock has to be smart?
