Deputies suggested to accelerate the entry into force of the law on personal data
If the initiative is successful, the data of Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015.
The State Duma has introduced a draft law that would move the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is listed in the lower house's legislative database.
It was authored by State Duma deputies Vadim Daygin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parahin ("Just Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (CPRF), and was supported by the Russian Federation.
According to the authors of the initiative, such a change will contribute to more efficient and effective ensuring the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the preservation of personal data and the observance of the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunication networks.
The law, which lawmakers are rushing to enact, requires that personal data of Russians processed via the Internet be stored in the territory of the Russian Federation.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, accumulate, store, clarify and extract personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as to indicate information about the location of such databases.
In addition, the law grants Roskomnadzor the right to restrict access to information processed in violation of Russian data protection law based on a court decision.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called "black lists" of offender sites - the automated information system "Registry of data subjects' rights violators".
This law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoy and Vadim Dygin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the KPRF.
Degengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill to postpone the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who don't have data centers in Russia will have to pay for the rent
Commenting on the bill submitted to the State Duma today, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy Leonid Levin said that he sees no problems with the postponement of the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own personal data storage facilities in the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "Rostelecom, which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent and already provides their servers, Mail Group, Western companies, which today already provide their servers".
"There are also several independent data centres willing to cooperate in this area", he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work in the territory of the Russian Federation, I see no problems - they will get technological opportunities for deployment", Levin concluded.
The controversial bill
Immediately after the bill was published, the Russian Association of Electronic Communications expressed concern that if the bill is passed, Russians will no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking services for air tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the bill deprives personal data subjects - citizens of the Russian Federation - of the right to dispose of their own data by imperatively determining that their recording, systematization, etc. must be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation".
The RAEC statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be to create a mechanism to inform the user about where the recording is carried out, systematizing his personal data.
In this case, the applicant can choose the territory in which the activities will be carried out.
The adoption of similar privacy localization bills in other countries has led to the demise of global services and significant economic losses.
