Savings certificate will be made nameless and irrevocable
The Treasury wants to ban bearer savings certificates, but will allow banks to make them the equivalent of a deposit.
The Treasury is drafting a bill that would ban bearer bonds.
Recently, this instrument has become popular, as the rates are higher than for bank deposits.
The fact is that the deposit-taker certificates are not covered by the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank, since it is not necessary to make contributions to the deposit insurance fund (DSA).
The irony is that this move is being made because of the small and medium-sized banks that distribute such certificates, and will affect Sberbank and Bank of Moscow, which, according to the ASV, controls 98% of the market.
The Bank of Moscow's share, according to the agency's calculations, is about 3.5%.
The problem, the ASB explains, is that customers of a small bank who have bought such a certificate, in case of revocation of its license, try to get money from the ASB.
Some investors, not being financially literate, may buy bearer certificates of savings and assume that their investments are insured.
The justified absence of insurance payments on these certificates in the event of a license revocation by the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the agency's practice, there have been cases where holders of pre-emption certificates have tried to recover insurance compensation through the court", the ASA said.
The problem is obviously far-fetched.
After all, no one will pay the buyers of the certificates anyway, because they have no legal right to compensation from the state.
If it were the case that the instrument was not insured in the ASV, then the ban would have been applied to the metal accounts, on which citizens' funds are accounted for in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
These accounts are not covered by the deposit insurance system, but their existence has not been questioned.
The thing is, most likely, that bearer bonds are a very convenient security that can actually act as a quasi-asset.
However, their movement is virtually uncontrollable: any bank customer can buy a certificate, pass it on to any citizen, and many owners can change before cashing such a certificate.
It is no accident that the bill stipulates that a savings certificate must be a securities of a specific name, which must be kept in a depository.
To give the banks a taste of the pill, such certificates are allowed to be issued without a right to early repayment.
So, it's the sort of no-return deposit that bankers have been dreaming of for a long time.
