Anger has become the most universal and functional emotion in man.
Angry facial expressions are biologically universal to humans, and each organ and muscle group involved in their creation is not random, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, Australian and U.S. scientists have found.
They reported their findings in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and a brief summary of their findings can be found in a news release from the University of California, Santa Barbara.
Angry facial expressions - raised and downward-sloping brows, thinly lined lips, and swollen nostrils - are common in all cultures, even among children who are blind from birth and have never seen him, notes lead researcher Aaron Sell.
In a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists have found that this emotion is created to effectively manage conflict.
The more physical damage one person can inflict on another, the more they have the ability to dictate their terms, and they communicate that to the other person through anger.
The researchers also found evidence for another hypothesis: Physically strong people are more likely to be angry and aggressive, to believe that they have the right to impose conditions that are not favorable to them, and to prefer violent conflict resolution over peaceful conflict resolution.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily a "bargaining emotion", the researchers decided that the movements of each of the seven groups of muscles that produce an angry facial expression should make the angry individual appear more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thus force him to agree to his terms as soon as possible in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers created a computer simulation of a face that had or had not each of the seven elements of an angry face, and showed them to the informants.
While lowered eyebrows and a raised chin alone did not make the face evil, the study participants unanimously agreed that the person depicted with these features was physically stronger.
In humans, as in animals, anger is a threat: an exaggerated display of one's own power, compelling one to comply and submit.
A man puffs his nostrils and presses his lips together for the same purpose as a frog who puffs himself up or a baboon who flaunts his fangs.
"Anger is triggered by the refusal of the other person to accept the situation, and the person immediately adopts a form that most effectively demonstrates the opposite side of the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of the angry face are arbitrary, they all express the same thing", noted anthropologist John Tooby.
The Ministry of Communications has proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to the "Crimea" TV and radio company
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget to the autonomous non-profit organization "Crimean Teleradio Company" in 2014.
This is stated in the draft government decree prepared by the agency, which was seen by "Lenta.ru".
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of a modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment".
In particular, the allocated money is supposed to re-equip the hardware-studio block, video walls, central hardware and video server room.
It is also planned to purchase a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter.
In addition, the company will use the funds to pay for the use of the fiber-optic communication line (FOPL) and the repair of the energy system.
The subsidies will be provided within the limits of the federal budget allocated to the Ministry of Communications.
The state broadcasting company "Crimea" was established in 1959, broadcasting in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
Today, the coverage of the television signal of the TV and radio company is more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, "Crimea" TV and Radio Company received a license to broadcast in digital format.
